body:
There are situations where CIRCT can produce assertions which will either no longer do anything or assertions which are actually dead. Consider the following:

```mlir
module {
  firrtl.circuit "Foo"  {
    firrtl.module @Foo() {
      %c1_ui1 = firrtl.constant 1 : !firrtl.uint<1>
      %0 = firrtl.asClock %c1_ui1 : (!firrtl.uint<1>) -> !firrtl.clock
      %_clock = firrtl.node %0  : !firrtl.clock
      %clock = firrtl.node sym @clock %_clock  : !firrtl.clock
      %_en = firrtl.node %c1_ui1  : !firrtl.uint<1>
      firrtl.assert %_clock, %c1_ui1, %c1_ui1, "hello"  {eventControl = 0 : i32, isConcurrent = true}
    }
  }
}
```

This produces (`firtool Foo.mlir --strip-debug-info`):
```verilog
module Foo();
  wire clock;

  assign clock = 1'h1;
  assert property (@(posedge 1'h1) 1'h1) else $error("hello");
  `ifdef USE_PROPERTY_AS_CONSTRAINT
    assume property (@(posedge 1'h1) 1'h1);
  `endif
endmodule
```

The final `assert` is wrong in two ways.  First the condition is always true meaning that the assertion will never fire. Additionally, the assertion may never actually be evaluated due to `@(posedge 1'h1)`. (I'm not sure about this... is this ever evaluated?) Certain tools, e.g., Yosys, are known to have problems with this (see: https://discourse.llvm.org/t/one-more-error-from-yosys/61181). These types of formulations should be canonicalized / DCE'd.
